explanation:
• OS_CHECK_POINTER (macro) — The macro may perform an early exit, longjmp, or call an assert/abort on NULL buffer; its expansion determines whether the code that follows can ever be reached.
• OS_CHECK_SIZE (macro) — Same as above for the nbytes check; can introduce an early return/abort that would make subsequent statements unreachable.
• OS_ObjectIdGetById (function) — Its return behavior and possible return values determine whether the if (return_code == OS_SUCCESS) branch can ever be taken; if it never returns OS_SUCCESS (or never returns at all) the inner block would be unreachable.
• OS_GenericWrite_Impl (function) — If this callee is annotated as noreturn or otherwise does not return (e.g., aborts or longjmps), then OS_ObjectIdRelease and the final return would be unreachable; need its prototype/attributes/semantics.
• OS_ObjectIdRelease (function/macro) — If this is implemented as a non-returning operation (or contains control-flow-altering behavior), it affects reachability of subsequent code; its implementation must be inspected.
• OS_SUCCESS (constant) — Needed to interpret the condition in the if-statement; understanding the value/contract helps determine whether the true branch is possible.
• OS_LOCK_MODE_REFCOUNT, LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE (macros/constants) — These arguments to OS_ObjectIdGetById can alter its behavior/contract; their definitions are required to reason whether OS_ObjectIdGetById can succeed and thus make the if-branch reachable.
• UtAssert_Abort (function used by assert/UT code) — Common target for check macros; if the check macros call an assert/abort function, this is the non-returning path that creates unreachable code.
• OS_object_token_t (type) — The token type may be a macro/union that affects whether OS_ObjectIdRelease or other calls are no-ops or have side effects that change control flow; include its definition.
• osal_id_t (type) — The id type may be typedef'd to a type with special semantics in macros/inline checks; include its definition.

These symbols (macros, constants, callees and any non‑returning assert) are necessary to determine whether any path in OS_TimedWrite contains statements that can never be executed (i.e., violate the MISRA rule against unreachable code).
